CTF Writeup: GDB Baby Step 3
picoCTF | Reverse Engineering Challenge


-----------------------------------------------------------
WHAT WAS THIS CHALLENGE?
-----------------------------------------------------------

One binary file was provided: debugger0_c. The value 0x2262c96b is loaded into
memory inside the main function. The goal was to examine that memory location
byte by byte using GDB and read the four bytes exactly as they are stored. The
flag is those four bytes combined in order with no spaces.

This challenge introduces a critical concept in computer architecture: endianness.


-----------------------------------------------------------
STEP 0 - Download the Binary
-----------------------------------------------------------

Command used:
wget https://artifacts.picoctf.net/c/[challenge-id]/debugger0_c

Verify the file is there:
ls

Then try:
cat debugger0_c

This prints unreadable gibberish because it is a compiled binary. We need GDB
to analyze it properly.

Remember: cat is for text files. Binaries need proper tools like GDB.


-----------------------------------------------------------
STEP 1 - Fix Permissions
-----------------------------------------------------------

Before opening in GDB, the binary needs execute permission or it will throw
a permission denied error when you try to run it.

Command used:
chmod +x debugger0_c

Or if that fails:
sudo chmod +x debugger0_c

Remember: downloaded binaries often do not have execute permission by default.
Always run chmod +x before trying to run or debug a binary.


-----------------------------------------------------------
STEP 2 - Open the Binary in GDB
-----------------------------------------------------------

Command used:
gdb debugger0_c

Then list all functions:
(gdb) info functions

This confirmed that main exists at address 0x0000000000401106.

Remember: always start with info functions to get a map of the binary before
doing anything else.


-----------------------------------------------------------
STEP 3 - Disassemble Main
-----------------------------------------------------------

Command used:
(gdb) disas main

Output:
   0x0000000000401106 <+0>:    endbr64
   0x000000000040110a <+4>:    push   %rbp
   0x000000000040110b <+5>:    mov    %rsp,%rbp
   0x000000000040110e <+8>:    mov    %edi,-0x14(%rbp)
   0x0000000000401111 <+11>:   mov    %rsi,-0x20(%rbp)
   0x0000000000401115 <+15>:   movl   $0x2262c96b,-0x4(%rbp)
   0x000000000040111c <+22>:   mov    -0x4(%rbp),%eax
   0x000000000040111f <+25>:   pop    %rbp
   0x0000000000401120 <+26>:   ret

The important line is:
   movl $0x2262c96b, -0x4(%rbp)

This stores the value 0x2262c96b into a local variable at -0x4(%rbp).
The instruction right after it at address 0x40111c is where we need to pause.

Remember: the movl line stores the value. The line right after it is where the
value is already in memory and ready to be examined.


-----------------------------------------------------------
STEP 4 - Set a Breakpoint and Run
-----------------------------------------------------------

We need to pause the program right after the value is stored in memory.
The instruction after the movl line is at address 0x40111c.

Commands used:
(gdb) break *0x40111c
(gdb) run

Output:
Breakpoint 1, 0x000000000040111c in main ()

The program paused exactly where we wanted. The value is now sitting in memory
at -0x4(%rbp).

Remember: breakpoints pause execution before that instruction runs. Setting it
at 0x40111c means the movl line already ran and the value is in memory.


-----------------------------------------------------------
STEP 5 - Examine the Memory Byte by Byte
-----------------------------------------------------------

Command used:
(gdb) x/4xb $rbp-0x4

Output:
0x7fffffffe1dc:   0x6b   0xc9   0x62   0x22

This printed four bytes starting from the memory address where the value
was stored. The x/4xb command means:
    x      = examine memory
    4      = show 4 units
    x      = display in hex
    b      = one byte at a time

Remember: do not use square brackets around the address. Write $rbp-0x4
not [$rbp-0x4]. Registers must use the $ prefix like $rbp not just rbp.


-----------------------------------------------------------
STEP 6 - Understand Endianness
-----------------------------------------------------------

The original value in the code was 0x2262c96b.
But the bytes in memory came out as: 0x6b 0xc9 0x62 0x22

Notice they are in reverse order compared to the original value. This is
because x86 processors use little-endian storage. Little-endian means the
smallest (least significant) byte is stored first in memory.

So 0x2262c96b gets stored in memory as:
    Address +0:   0x6b   (least significant byte first)
    Address +1:   0xc9
    Address +2:   0x62
    Address +3:   0x22   (most significant byte last)

The challenge says the flag is the bytes exactly as they appear in memory.
The example given was: if you see 0x11 0x22 0x33 0x44, the flag is
picoCTF{0x11223344}. So we just read them left to right as printed.

Remember: do not reverse the bytes. The flag uses the memory order, not the
original value order. Little-endian is why they look backwards compared to
what was written in the source.


-----------------------------------------------------------
STEP 7 - Build the Flag
-----------------------------------------------------------

Bytes in memory in order:
0x6b   0xc9   0x62   0x22

Combined with no spaces:
0x6bc96222

Remember: concatenate the bytes exactly as printed, left to right, dropping
the individual 0x prefixes and adding one 0x at the front.


